<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!--
  egpt-tick.xml — Task Scheduler task that wakes the OS every PT10M so
  the NSSM-managed egpt-daemon service gets execution time even during
  long Modern Standby naps. The TASK does almost nothing (one cmd line
  appends a timestamp); the WAKE is the point.

  Why this exists: on this hardware class (Ryzen 7 7730U, S0LPI only)
  Modern Standby can suppress the service's scheduler windows during
  long deep-sleep stretches — and if egpt sits suspended for an hour
  it misses outbox sends, heartbeat cadences, and any other due work.
  PT10M wake bounds the miss-window to 10 minutes maximum.

  This task does NOT replace the NSSM service. It complements it. The
  service is the spine; this task just nudges the OS to schedule it.

  Install via setup/install-tick-task.cmd (auto-elevates, prompts once
  for the password to register S4U principal).
  Uninstall via setup/uninstall-tick-task.cmd.
-->
<Task version="1.4" xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/windows/2004/02/mit/task">
  <RegistrationInfo>
    <Author>egpt</Author>
    <URI>\egpt-tick</URI>
    <Description>Wake-the-OS hedge for the egpt-daemon NSSM service. Fires every PT10M with WakeToRun=true. Action is a one-line cmd append to ~/.egpt/logs/egpt-tick.log; the wake side effect is what matters - it ensures the always-running egpt-daemon service gets execution time at least every 10 minutes even during Modern Standby DRIPS / Austerity sub-states. Combined with NSSM-as-service, this gives bounded miss-windows for heartbeats / outbox sends / scheduled rollups.</Description>
  </RegistrationInfo>
  <Triggers>
    <!--
      6 staggered triggers at 10s offsets, repeating PT8M (operator
      2026-06-06, deconstruct phase IV - the BATTERY-SPACING test).

      Sequence so far:
        6@10s PT1M battery-per-minute    -> worked, BUT @e replies
                                            were suspiciously fast,
                                            suggesting the firmware
                                            never actually descended
                                            to deep DRIPS / Austerity
        1 / 2 / 3 trigger variants       -> failed
        6@10s PT7M (6m10s silence)       -> too short for descent
        6@10s PT8M (7m10s silence)       -> testing now (this XML)

      Hypothesis: Modern Standby has multiple depth levels (S0i1
      light idle, S0i2/i3 deeper, DRIPS, Austerity). The firmware
      only descends to the deepest after sustained quiet. If a
      6-trigger battery fires every 60 seconds, the firmware
      probably keeps us at a shallow level the whole time - which
      means we never test 'real' Modern Standby and the fast @e
      reply was the shallow-state speed, not a true wake-from-deep.

      Battery span = 50s (6 fires at 10s offsets from 00:00 to 00:50).
      PT8M cycle - 50s battery = 7m10s of true quiet between batteries.
      That's cleanly above the typical DRIPS descent threshold (~1-2
      min on consumer firmware), so the firmware has real time to
      deepen.

      During a 10-min nap: ~1-2 batteries fire (at 0 and possibly 8 min).
      If @e responds via these, the architecture truly handles
      deep lid-down sleep.

      Don't reduce battery count below 6 (already proven necessary).
      Tune PT8M up/down based on what test results look like.
    -->
    <TimeTrigger>
      <StartBoundary>2026-01-01T00:00:00</StartBoundary>
      <Enabled>true</Enabled>
      <Repetition>
        <Interval>PT8M</Interval>
        <StopAtDurationEnd>false</StopAtDurationEnd>
      </Repetition>
    </TimeTrigger>
    <TimeTrigger>
      <StartBoundary>2026-01-01T00:00:10</StartBoundary>
      <Enabled>true</Enabled>
      <Repetition>
        <Interval>PT8M</Interval>
        <StopAtDurationEnd>false</StopAtDurationEnd>
      </Repetition>
    </TimeTrigger>
    <TimeTrigger>
      <StartBoundary>2026-01-01T00:00:20</StartBoundary>
      <Enabled>true</Enabled>
      <Repetition>
        <Interval>PT8M</Interval>
        <StopAtDurationEnd>false</StopAtDurationEnd>
      </Repetition>
    </TimeTrigger>
    <TimeTrigger>
      <StartBoundary>2026-01-01T00:00:30</StartBoundary>
      <Enabled>true</Enabled>
      <Repetition>
        <Interval>PT8M</Interval>
        <StopAtDurationEnd>false</StopAtDurationEnd>
      </Repetition>
    </TimeTrigger>
    <TimeTrigger>
      <StartBoundary>2026-01-01T00:00:40</StartBoundary>
      <Enabled>true</Enabled>
      <Repetition>
        <Interval>PT8M</Interval>
        <StopAtDurationEnd>false</StopAtDurationEnd>
      </Repetition>
    </TimeTrigger>
    <TimeTrigger>
      <StartBoundary>2026-01-01T00:00:50</StartBoundary>
      <Enabled>true</Enabled>
      <Repetition>
        <Interval>PT8M</Interval>
        <StopAtDurationEnd>false</StopAtDurationEnd>
      </Repetition>
    </TimeTrigger>
  </Triggers>
  <Principals>
    <Principal id="Author">
      <UserId>REVE\an</UserId>
      <LogonType>Password</LogonType>
      <RunLevel>LeastPrivilege</RunLevel>
    </Principal>
  </Principals>
  <Settings>
    <MultipleInstancesPolicy>IgnoreNew</MultipleInstancesPolicy>
    <DisallowStartIfOnBatteries>false</DisallowStartIfOnBatteries>
    <StopIfGoingOnBatteries>false</StopIfGoingOnBatteries>
    <AllowHardTerminate>false</AllowHardTerminate>
    <StartWhenAvailable>true</StartWhenAvailable>
    <RunOnlyIfNetworkAvailable>false</RunOnlyIfNetworkAvailable>
    <IdleSettings>
      <StopOnIdleEnd>false</StopOnIdleEnd>
      <RestartOnIdle>false</RestartOnIdle>
    </IdleSettings>
    <AllowStartOnDemand>true</AllowStartOnDemand>
    <Enabled>true</Enabled>
    <Hidden>false</Hidden>
    <RunOnlyIfIdle>false</RunOnlyIfIdle>
    <UseUnifiedSchedulingEngine>true</UseUnifiedSchedulingEngine>
    <WakeToRun>true</WakeToRun>
    <ExecutionTimeLimit>PT1M</ExecutionTimeLimit>
    <Priority>7</Priority>
  </Settings>
  <Actions Context="Author">
    <Exec>
      <Command>cmd.exe</Command>
      <Arguments>/c "C:\Users\an\src\egpt\setup\egpt-tick.cmd"</Arguments>
      <WorkingDirectory>C:\Users\an</WorkingDirectory>
    </Exec>
  </Actions>
</Task>
